                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "The nurse is caring for a pediatric client who just arrived at the emergency department with an extremity fracture. The nurse uses the five \"Ps\" to assess the extent of the client's injury. What are some of the five \"Ps\"? Select all that apply.",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "a0f7d178f7b728b8bba7ef20ddeca62d",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Evaluating 评价",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nIf a child sustains a fracture, the extent of the injury is immediately assessed using the five \"P's\"—pain and point of tenderness, pulses distal (not proximal) to the fracture site, pallor, paresthesia (sensation) distal to the fracture site, and paralysis (movement distal to fracture site).\n\nClient Needs: Physiological Integrity\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Recognize Cues\nCognitive Ability: Applying\nContent Area: Health Assessment/Physical Exam: Musculoskeletal\nHealth Problem: Pediatric-Specific: Fractures\nIntegrated Process: Nursing Process/Assessment\nPriority Concepts: Pain, Perfusion\nStrategies: Subject\n   Test-Taking Strategy:\nNote the subject, the five \"Ps\" and assessing an extremity fracture. The five \"Ps\" must be identified correctly to help the nurse assess the fracture correctly. Think about the pathophysiology associated with a fracture. Also, noting the word proximal in option 4 will assist in eliminating this option.\n \n   ",
                        "id": "8e2cd356b15e4dba871b104353010ae0",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
